            \– must have a great summer vibe

  .article-section.article-section-right-image.text-first.article-half-page-image-floated
    .article-text
      %h3
        The basic requirements of a summer beach bag

      .article-image.aspect-1
        -image_url = image_path("blog/summer-beach-bag/bag-on-beach.jpg")
        =image_tag(image_url, alt: "A woven straw bag sits on a white sandy beach with a wide-brimmed hat resting against it and the sea in the background. The bag holds suncream, flip-flops, and a colourful beach towel.")
        %figcaption
          Photo by
          =link_to('awesomecontent', 'https://www.freepik.com/free-photo/bag-with-beach-accessories-kept-sand_991183.htm')
          on Freepik

      %p
        Once again, expectations can be high once you have reached your chosen destination and why not?
        You have spent your hard earned cash on booking some quality down time and you want it to be filled with more fun and less hassle and to go smoothly, so it’s important to do a little ‘thinking ahead’ before you leave.
        So, let's take a quick look at what it is that we expect from our hard working beach bag on our annual summer vay-cay?

      %p
        Here are some key essential components for any holiday beach bag.
        Taking a minute to look at these now will save you from bad choices or forgotten items whilst you are away so your time in the sun is hassle free and all you dreamed of.

      %h4
        1. Strong – able to hold everything
      %p
        If I know myself well in any way, I would say that strength is always a key factor for my beach bag.
        I need to know that it is going to hold up on holiday and take any heavy stuff like my 10 litre bottle of sun screen.

      %h4
        2. Good handles – no time for breakages
      %p
        Yes! That’s right I want to be too busy enjoying myself to think about whether my beach bag's handles are going to last the holiday or not.

      %h4
        3. Compartments
      %p
        There is absolutely no time for rummaging in my beach bag.
        I want to be able to find what I need really quick and get back to enjoying my beach time.

      %h4
        4. The right size
      %p
        My beach bag has definitely got to be adaptable and it has to fit everything I need for the beach, like my beach towel that is big enough for 3 people, and I want room to spare.

      %h4
        5. Easy to keep clean
      %p
        Beaches are messy and let’s face it there is sand everywhere, so being able to keep everything inside 100% sand free and clean is a non-negotiable for sure.

      %h4
        6. How does it look
      %p
        Does it has a good summer vibe? The last thing any girl wants is shame on the beach. My beach bag had to be beach ready too. No shame in my beach game.


  .article-section.article-section-right-image.text-first.article-half-page-image-floated
    .article-text
      %h3
        Size is definitely important

      .article-image.aspect-1
        -image_url = image_path("blog/summer-beach-bag/beach-bags-on-bench.jpg")
        =image_tag(image_url, alt: "A collection of beach bags stacked on a wooden bench in front of a wooden building. The bench and building are painted in a pale blue and the overall image has a casual beach vibe.")
        %figcaption
          Photo by
          =link_to('Sanddollar', 'https://www.pexels.com/photo/six-assorted-colors-tote-bags-on-white-wooden-cabinet-634538')
          on Pexels

    .article-text
      %p
        There is probably nothing worse when it comes to beach bags, than dealing with an overstuffed beach bag sat right there in the sand like a sack of potatoes.
        If it will not close then there is a good chance it will remain sand free and there is rarely a safe clean space to empty your beach bag out as you go looking for things and need to repack.
        In my experience there is a good chance that everything is going to get covered in sand and I may even lose something important right there on the beach whilst repacking for the millionth time.
        My advice is to take a good look at all the items you think you will want on the beach and pick a bag that will easily accommodate these from the start.
        Be honest with yourself about what you need and you will find it easier to pick the right bag.

      %h3
        Style versus practicality

      %p
        Picking a good bag can be difficult and there can be many angles to look at.
        I always have a 50/50 split on this subject.
        Yes I want my beach bag to look good but wait, I need it to be super practical too.
        Some beach items (like towels for instance) can be big and cumbersome, and what if you are the donkey for your beach party and you have to get more than one towel to fit in?
        One beach towel alone can fill any unsuspecting beach bag right to the top.
        Who wants a tiny tea-towel sized beach towel to sit on all day?


      .quick-guide-container.quick-guide-beach
        .quick-guide.quick-guide-wide
          %h4.quick-guide-title
            Handy tip
          %p
            I once tested a shoe bag for my towel and found it a great idea.
            Because they fold down to nothing and are extremely lightweight it was so practical.
            Also, it meant that I could have a smaller beach bag and I never had to put my wet or sandy towel in with my dry clothes or other things. 

      %br
      %p
        So, whether you go for practicality or for style, or you want some of both, there is an ideal beach bag for you.


